dismissalText.commentary: AB de Villiers c Jordan b Stokes 73 (91b 4x4 1x6 117m) SR: 80.21

dismissalComment.html: full and dispatched high into the leg side... hang on, that's coming down with ice on it, and Jordan makes the catch! Brilliant work, running back to take a steepler over his shoulder, diving full length - never in doubt with that man. AB has been gunned down just as he looked to be getting going

headshotImage.longCaption: Reece Topley player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Jean-Paul Duminy lbw b Topley 47 (66b 2x4 0x6 83m) SR: 71.21

dismissalComment.html: pitched up and Duminy is hit on the pads, aiming a drive down the ground... and given! Looked a little leg side but SA used their review for de Kock's dismissal so Duminy will have to drag himself away. Yes, Hawk-Eye shows the ball missing leg stump, not a great decision but, in this case, the umpire's word is final

headshotImage.caption: Reece Topley player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Reece Topley player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalComment.html: gottim, off stump rattled! Amla is bowled off his pads, he's not enjoyed this angle of attack and Topley gets one through his defences, it shaped back but Amla played the wrong line, past the outside edge and flicking the back leg - would have been plumb lbw if the ball hadn't deflected on to off stump. It was actually a cracking ball, looked to be swinging and then nipped away

beats him on the inside, Buttler sprawls to take the catch low to his right... Topley appeals, Morgan likes it and England decide to review. Lots of high fives among the England players but Rossouw is calling for new gloves... Who's right? The ball was full and swinging in, Rossouw chopped down on it, possibly the sound was the bat hitting the ground. Can't see an obvious deflection and Ultra Edge is struggling to differentiate between the ball passing the bat and the bat hitting the ground. Think this will stay not out... But what do I know! Given, caught behind!

dismissalComment.html: short, pulled, gloved ... on my Lord, what has Hales done?! It took an eternity for the finger to go up but his guilty look probably pulled his own trigger! A lobbed chance to de Kock as Hales grabbed at his chance for three figures, and well, that non-jinxy statement has had its non-intended non-effect!

dismissalComment.html: nailed him! That is just the sweetest dismissal for a fast bowler, full length, fast, nipping off the seam and steam-rollering through the gate as Roy propped forward in an otherwise impeccable forward defence! The gap was there for a fraction of a second, and he dived straight through it like Indiana Jones rolling under a cave door

The Gopher of Economy has morphed into the Woodchuck of Penetration, he perhaps saw Root coming and dropped short, cramped him for space and he could only deflect the ball down on to his stumps

commentTextItems.html: smashed through midwicket, game over!

commentPostTextItems.html: 5.48pm A few thoughts from the presentations. First up, AB de Villiers. "We were about 20 short," he says. ""290-300 would have been ideal. I think JP got an unlucky one, they felt a little hard done-by, it was still a competitive total but credit to the opposition, they played a good game of cricket and out-thought us."
"It was a good cricket wicket throughout the 100 overs. No excuses, we were out-played."

Eoin Morgan: "Completely different conditions, the challenge today was adapting, the game was in the balance but Jos Buttler took the game into his own hands. We were very happy with 260, and given the way we've been playing with the bat, it was within range."
Morgan said he bowled his spinners straight through in a bid to get AB de Villiers out, which was a cunning captaincy ploy.

Unsurprisingly, the Man of the Match is Alex Hales for his 99: "A different sort of innings required today, we knew if we took it deep we'd get over the line. The Test series was difficult but I learnt a lot and since we switched to the white ball, it've felt in good touch."
So that is that. Join us again in Centurion on Tuesday for the third ODI, and have a read of David Hopps' match report. From myself and Alan Gardner, goodbye.

5.38pm Well, that was brisk. England's one-day renaissance shows no sign of slowing down ... actually, renaissance rather implies they were ever any good in the format (humble apologies to Goochie's class of 92, of course...). This is a team with the means to go a long, long way in the coming years. THey have class acts in all departments, and in Jos Buttler, a gun batsman who can win in style from any situation. Today was about Alex Hales' solidity at the top of the order, fine bowling from the spin twins, Moeen and Adil Rashid, and a career-best 4 for 50 from young Reece Topley. England are 2-0 up, and despite a return to form for AB de Villiers, South Africa were second-best by some distance again today.

soham: "amazing turnaround by the english team after wc debacle.never seen such a attacking positive english odi team before!cant say about 2019 wc because its too far but for 2017 champions trophy this team is alreasy a contender!" Troo dat ... and I wouldn't be surprised if they were contenders in the World Twenty20 too...

SanjayN: "Last 5 overs, 61 runs. Says it all. Well played, England, too good again for SA. Mumbai Indians got Buttler for a steal. Just compare the silly money that's been paid out for some seriously mediocre players."

commentTextItems.html: Moeen's turn to have a mow! A typical range-hitting stand-and-deliver blow, straight back whence it came. One bounce and into the rope
a rare dot-ball, but too little too late, that is a massive 21-run over

headshotImage.caption: Kagiso Rabada player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Kagiso Rabada player page headshot cutout, 2021

commentTextItems.html: flogged! Monstrous cross-batted assault, down on one knee, not a ring in sight though as Tahir is jilted into the stands, back over his head!
mowed over midwicket! Buttler can't be bothered to nudge and nurdle England to victory, he's got a long handle and he intends to use it!
big stride, head over the ball, clears the front leg, battered into the stands. Fetch!
Ali escapes the strike, as well he might
chipped in the air ... Berhardien at long-off galloped across but it is dropped! Think Jordan's catch but much easier ...

commentPostTextItems.html: Hoover: "If Buttler isn't motivated to perform after earning many a pretty penny today, he never will be!" I'd have thought the reverse would be true. Stick on the shades and the dollar-shaped bling, and chill in the dug-out. I'm alright Jack ...

commentTextItems.html: very full once again, Buttler gets in a tangle as he attempts to work the ball away. Good tight work

headshotImage.caption: Kagiso Rabada player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Kagiso Rabada player page headshot cutout, 2021

commentTextItems.html: on the pads, full again, worked into the leg side

commentPostTextItems.html: Swapnil: "Hales becomes the sixth batsman to get out in 99 in odi for england.. if I am using the statsguru right." Your skills have not let you down ...

commentTextItems.html: dead-batted to mid-off, and a sharp call allows them to scamper home before the shy comes in
full and straight, Rabada doing all he can to keep South Africa in the hunt
driven off the back foot, but can't pick the gap
another single, England easing along now
crunched through backward square, and that is surely the game. A volley of runs, 12 in three balls, 16 off the over, and England's equation looks serene once again

headshotImage.caption: Kagiso Rabada player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Kagiso Rabada player page headshot cutout, 2021

commentTextItems.html: slower ball, and that's a fine riposte, bunted through midwicket, and picks the gap nicely. Too short at that pace
edged, but the keeper can't intercept! Nothing you can do as a bowler about that, a perfect ball, climbing at the edge, but without a slip in place what can you do?
short, pulled through midwicket, a measured placement of a pull rather than a full-blooded mow
poked back down the pitch, Abbott gathers in his followthrough
dabbed out to cover

commentPostTextItems.html: Naman: "This is the beauty of such pitches. Most of the games on flat wickets are one-sided but on these kind of wickets, a 260 run target makes for a fantastic contest. You just never know what's gonna happen." Quite so. Four big overs from Abbott and Rabada, and who knows?

dismissalComment.html: gottim, off stump rattled! Amla is bowled off his pads, he's not enjoyed this angle of attack and Topley gets one through his defences, it shaped back but Amla played the wrong line, past the outside edge and flicking the back leg - would have been plumb lbw if the ball hadn't deflected on to off stump. It was actually a cracking ball, looked to be swinging and then nipped away

headshotImage.caption: Ben Stokes player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Ben Stokes player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Quinton de Kock lbw b Stokes 22 (33b 4x4 0x6 47m) SR: 66.66

dismissalComment.html: on the stumps, straightening a touch and de Kock misses playing across the line... Dharmasena gives it! The batsman is going to review and only the matter of whether it pitched outside leg can save him now, you feel. It's definitely homing in on the stumps - and Hawk-Eye has it just pitching in line! De Kock's appeal fails, he's been dismissed for the first time in the series and Ben Stokes has made something happen for his team again

headshotImage.caption: Adil Rashid player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Adil Rashid player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Faf du Plessis c Jordan b Rashid 46 (48b 4x4 1x6 76m) SR: 95.83

dismissalComment.html: pitches, grips, edged, gone! Du Plessis tried to angle his shot into the leg side, he was seduced by the drift but beaten by the spin as that one took a leading outside edge, for Jordan to tumble well and gather at slip!

headshotImage.caption: Ben Stokes player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Ben Stokes player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: AB de Villiers c Jordan b Stokes 73 (91b 4x4 1x6 117m) SR: 80.21

dismissalComment.html: full and dispatched high into the leg side... hang on, that's coming down with ice on it, and Jordan makes the catch! Brilliant work, running back to take a steepler over his shoulder, diving full length - never in doubt with that man. AB has been gunned down just as he looked to be getting going

headshotImage.caption: Reece Topley player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Reece Topley player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Jean-Paul Duminy lbw b Topley 47 (66b 2x4 0x6 83m) SR: 71.21

dismissalComment.html: pitched up and Duminy is hit on the pads, aiming a drive down the ground... and given! Looked a little leg side but SA used their review for de Kock's dismissal so Duminy will have to drag himself away. Yes, Hawk-Eye shows the ball missing leg stump, not a great decision but, in this case, the umpire's word is final

headshotImage.caption: Reece Topley player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Reece Topley player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Rilee Rossouw c †Buttler b Topley 11 (11b 2x4 0x6 23m) SR: 100

dismissalComment.html: beats him on the inside, Buttler sprawls to take the catch low to his right... Topley appeals, Morgan likes it and England decide to review. Lots of high fives among the England players but Rossouw is calling for new gloves... Who's right? The ball was full and swinging in, Rossouw chopped down on it, possibly the sound was the bat hitting the ground. Can't see an obvious deflection and Ultra Edge is struggling to differentiate between the ball passing the bat and the bat hitting the ground. Think this will stay not out... But what do I know! Given, caught behind!

headshotImage.longCaption: Kagiso Rabada player page headshot cutout, 2021

headshotImage.caption: Kagiso Rabada player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Kagiso Rabada player page headshot cutout, 2021

headshotImage.caption: Reece Topley player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Reece Topley player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Kagiso Rabada c Morgan b Topley 12 (10b 1x4 0x6 16m) SR: 120

dismissalComment.html: slower ball, Rabada swipes at it... top-edged to backward point! Smartly bowled, out the back of the hand and anticipating the attempt to go hard at the ball, looped up tamely to Morgan pedaling back to his right

headshotImage.caption: Jason Roy player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Jason Roy player page headshot cutout, 2021

headshotImage.caption: Jason Roy player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Jason Roy player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Jason Roy b Abbott 14 (13b 3x4 0x6 11m) SR: 107.69

dismissalComment.html: nailed him! That is just the sweetest dismissal for a fast bowler, full length, fast, nipping off the seam and steam-rollering through the gate as Roy propped forward in an otherwise impeccable forward defence! The gap was there for a fraction of a second, and he dived straight through it like Indiana Jones rolling under a cave door

dismissalText.commentary: Alex Hales c †de Kock b Abbott 99 (124b 8x4 0x6 179m) SR: 79.83

dismissalComment.html: short, pulled, gloved ... on my Lord, what has Hales done?! It took an eternity for the finger to go up but his guilty look probably pulled his own trigger! A lobbed chance to de Kock as Hales grabbed at his chance for three figures, and well, that non-jinxy statement has had its non-intended non-effect!

dismissalText.commentary: Joe Root b Abbott 38 (64b 2x4 0x6 93m) SR: 59.37

dismissalComment.html: on the move, tucked up, angled bat... and Root plays on! South Africa have their breakthrough and it's Abbott again! The Gopher of Economy has morphed into the Woodchuck of Penetration, he perhaps saw Root coming and dropped short, cramped him for space and he could only deflect the ball down on to his stumps

dismissalText.commentary: Eoin Morgan c de Villiers b Morkel 29 (28b 1x4 2x6 43m) SR: 103.57

dismissalComment.html: a massive mow as Morgan is fractionally deceived by a slower ball, Morkel rolls his fingers down the side of the ball, de Villiers steadies himself at deep midwicket, and takes a vital breakthrough catch!

headshotImage.caption: Ben Stokes player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Ben Stokes player page headshot cutout, 2021

headshotImage.caption: Ben Stokes player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Ben Stokes player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Ben Stokes b Morkel 0 (6b 0x4 0x6 11m) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: bowled him! Stokes hasn't looked comfortable at all in this innings, the slower deck working against him perhaps. Morkel angles one across the left-hander, cramping him for room outside off, and the ball doesn't get up much, cannons off the inside edge and into the stumps!

dismissalText.commentary: Jos Buttler not out 48 (28b 4x4 3x6 42m) SR: 171.42
Moeen Ali not out 21 (15b 3x4 0x6 24m) SR: 140
